es of the period. The practices considered range from deliberation and inscription to publication and profanity. The narratives under construction range from secularisation to the rise of majority rule. Many of the authors also examine ways British developments were affected by and in turn influenced the world outside of Britain. These chapter will be essential reading for students of early modern Britain, early modern Europe and the Atlantic World. They will also appeal to those interested in the religious and political history of other regions and periods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Stuart Era (1603-1714).2bisacsh  aElizabethan.  aPeter Lake.  aStuart.  aparliament.  apost-revisionism.  apublic sphere.  apuritans.  arecusants.  asuccession crisis.  atrans-Atlantic.1 aBellany, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulman, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulman, William J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aComo, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowan, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomínguez, Freddy C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomínguez, Freddy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKane, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillstone, Noah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMishra, Rupali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShagan, Ethan H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStephens, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators